title: For Sale:  L.C. Smith Pigeon Grade 12 ga. W / 2 Barrel & Case
postcontent: This is a rare L.C. Smith Pigeon grade 12 ga. SxS shotgun. This shotgun was made in 1902 by The Hunter Arms Co. Of Fulton NY. It comes with two, serial number matching, sets of factory barrels. There were only 1350 12 ga Pigeon grade shotguns made and far far fewer with an extra matched set of barrels. Additional features that add to the rarity is that it is equipped with ejectors and the Hunter One (single) Trigger. The receiver still shows most if not all of it's fine engraving. Most of the case colors have faded. There is still a little on the water table and on the upper tang under the lever. At some point it was it was subject to some heavy handed gunsmithing. A few of the screw slots are buggered and there are a few marks on the edges where the lock plates fit in the receiver. The deluxe French walnut stock may have had some finish applied at some point. The LOP is 13 7/8" to the end of the pad. It may have been ordered with a short stock. The butt end of the wood is still curved and doesn't look like it has been cut. the spacer and pad have been added. There is a fine hairline crack starting at the back end of each lock plate at about the 10:00 position traveling back, up and around to the end of the upper tang. It is much easier to see on the left side than the right. The lock up is tight with both barrels and the lever rests right of center when closed. Barrel set number 1 is 30" Chainette Damascus choked full and full. It retains 90 to 95% of the bold Damascus pattern. There are just a few rub/fade areas, mostly at the camber end and around the muzzle. The bores are excellent. Very shiny no rust or pitting. The left is perfect the right has one very small dent. The chambers are bright with a small amount of rough area. The splinter style for end has a few dents on the wood edge, one fairly substantial. It has an ivory center bead and a brass bead at the muzzle. Barrel set number 2 are 28" Nitro Steel choked Modified and Improved. They retain 90 to 95% of the original blue but do show moderate spotting down the length of it. The bores are very good, shiny with just a little bit of roughness in areas, no dents. It has just the brass bead. The splinter fore arm for this set is in good condition. The barrel and fore arm are stamped with the number 2 for second set. The barrel is stamped on the fore arm lug and the fore end on the iron. Included is the high quality reproduction L.C. Smith luggage style gun case with two brass snap caps and the oil bottle. It is a beautiful gun as is or maybe good candidate for a full restoration.
